revision.text:
{{Infobox person | name = Agresphon | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = Greek | other_names = | occupation = [[Philologist]] | years_active = | known_for = }} '''Agresphon''' ([[ancient Greek|Gr.]] '''{{lang|grc|Ἀγρέσφων}}'''), or possibly '''Agreophon''', was an [[ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] [[Philologist|grammarian]] mentioned in the ''[[Suda]]''.<ref>''Suda'', ''s.v.'' {{lang|grc|Ἀπολλώνιος}}</ref> He wrote a work on persons with [[homonym]]ous names, sometimes called in English ''On Namesakes'' ({{lang|grc|Περὶ Ὁμωνύμων}}).
Agresphon cannot have lived earlier than the reign of [[Hadrian]], as in his work he spoke of an [[Apollonius the Sophist|Apollonius]] who lived in the time of that emperor.<ref name="DGRBM">{{Cite book | last = Mason | first = Charles Peter | contribution = Agresphon | editor-last = Smith | editor-first = William | title = [[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]] | volume = 1 | pages = 75 | publisher = [[Little, Brown and Company]] | place = Boston | year = 1867 | contribution-url = http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0084.html }}</ref> Scholars generally date him to the late 3rd or early 4th century.<ref name="df"/>
Agresphon's book on homonymous people was thought to have been similar to, or perhaps dependent upon, a work by [[Demetrius of Magnesia]], which bears the same title, and was written around the 1st century BC.<ref name="df"/> There is some debate as to whether his name was properly "Agresphon" or "Agreophon".<ref name="df">{{cite book | last = Schepens | first = G. | title = Die Fragmente Der Griechischen Historiker: Continued | publisher = [[Brill Publishers]] | year = 1998 | location = Leiden | pages = 258–260 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wOTq8nXKIWoC| isbn = 90-04-11304-5}}</ref>
Another, unrelated Agreophon who was father of [[Zeno of Caunus|Zenon]] around the 3rd century BC is mentioned frequently in the [[papyrus|papyri]] of the [[Zenon Archive]].
