{{Infobox noble|type | name = Manfred | title = prince of Sicily | image = Coat of Arms of Eleanor of Sicily, Queen of Aragon.svg | image_size = 120px | caption = Coat of arms of Aragonese Sicily | succession = [[Duke of Athens]] & [[Neopatria]] | predecessor = [[Roger Deslaur]] | successor = [[William II, Duke of Athens]] | reign = 1312 - 1317 | spouse = | issue = | noble family = [[House of Barcelona|of Barcelona]] | father = [[Frederick III of Sicily|Frederick II of Sicily]] | mother = [[Eleanor of Anjou]] | birth_name = | birth_date = 1306 | birth_place = | death_date = 9 November 1317 | death_place = [[Trapani]] | burial_date = | burial_place = Dominican church of Trapani | religion = [[Catholic Church]] }}
'''Manfred''' (1306 &ndash; 9 November 1317), ''[[infante]]'' of [[Kingdom of Sicily|Sicily]], was the second son of [[Frederick III of Sicily]] and [[Eleanor of Anjou]].
He was appointed [[Duke of Athens]] and [[Neopatria]] in 1312 by his father at the request of the knights of the [[Catalan Company]] then in control of [[Athens]]. Manfred was only five when he was named Duke. His father sent [[Berenguer Estañol de Ampurias|Berenguer Estañol]] as his [[regent]].
In 1316, [[Alfonso Fadrique]], Manfred's elder (but illegitimate) brother, was appointed [[vicar general]] of Athens. The young Duke never set foot in his realm, however, for he died in a fall from his horse before his twelfth birthday. He died in [[Trapani]] and was buried in the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] church located there. His younger brother [[William II of Athens|William]] succeeded him as Duke.
